{"title_page": "J. C. Hall (poet)", "text_new": "{{For|the Canadian author|J. C. Hall (disambiguation){{!}}J. C. Hall}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name = J. C. Hall\n| image =\n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = John Clive Hall\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|09|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Ealing, London\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2011|10|14|1920|9|12|df=y}}\n| death_place = Tunbridge Wells, Kent\n| resting_place = \n| occupation = Poet\n| language = English\n| nationality = British\n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Oriel College, Oxford]]\n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp = \n| ethnicity = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n}}\n\n'''John Clive Hall''' (12 September 1920 \u2013 14 October 2011) was an [[England|English]] [[poet]] and editor.\n\n== Poetry ==\nHall's poetry was first published when he was aged seventeen in the anthology, ''The Best Poems of 1938''.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The best Poems of 1938 |last=Moult |first=Thomas |publisher=Jonathan Cape |year=1938 |isbn= |location= |pages=}}</ref> He subsequently wrote and published a trickle of short poems over seven further decades. Not a modernist, he was included in [[Dannie Abse]]'s 'reactionary anthology' ''Mavericks''.<ref>{{Cite book |title= Mavericks - An Anthology |last= |first= |publisher= Editions Poetry And Poverty |year=1957 |isbn= |editor1= Abse, Dannie |editor2= Sergeant, Howard |location= |pages=}}</ref> His work was admired by [[Philip Larkin]] who described it as, \"just the sort of thing I should like to have done myself\" and by [[W. H. Auden]] who wrote \"in the poems of J. C. Hall we see a craftsmanship that yields to the reader constant pleasure and enjoyment. J. C. Hall should be better known.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Long-Shadows-J-C-Hall/dp/0571272657 |title=Long Shadows |first=J. C. |last=Hall |date=19 August 2010 |publisher=Faber & Faber |via=Amazon}}</ref> A Trevor Tolley judged \"his work has a carefulness that makes one ready to accept his small output as a mark of spiritual and poetic integrity\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tolley |first1=A. Trevor |title=The Poetry of the Forties |date=1985 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1708-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/poetryoffortiesi0000toll |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/poetryoffortiesi0000toll/page/258 258] |quote=Fords and Bridges. |language=en}}</ref>.\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in Ealing, London and brought up in [[Royal Tunbridge Wells|Tunbridge Wells]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/8882163/JC-Hall.html |title=J. C. Hall Obituary |date=10 November 2011 |publisher=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=31 December 2017 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Hall attended [[Leighton Park School]] and [[Oriel College, Oxford]].{{sfn|Noel-Tod|Hamilton|2013|p=239}} He was an editor of the literary periodical ''[[Fords and Bridges]]'' at Oxford and became good friends with [[Keith Douglas]].{{sfn|Noel-Tod|Hamilton|2013|p=239}} As a pacifist he did farm work during the war and when Douglas was killed in Normandy, Hall was named as his literary executor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.faber.co.uk/author/jc-hall/ |title=J.C. Hall - Authors - Faber & Faber |website=www.faber.co.uk}}</ref> He worked at ''[[The London Magazine]]'' and at [[Stephen Spender]]'s ''[[Encounter (magazine)|Encounter]]'' as an editor.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He edited the Collected Poems of [[Edwin Muir]] for Faber and Faber in 1952.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Muir |first1=Edwin |title=Collected Poems 1921-1951 |date=1952 |publisher=Faber and Faber}}</ref> A group photographic portrait of Hall, with fellow poets Dannie Abse, [[David Wright (poet)|David John Murray Wright]], [[Anthony Cronin]] and John Smith is held by the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw233563/David-John-Murray-Wright-Anthony-Cronin-John-Clive-JC-Hall-John-Smith-Dannie-Abse?LinkID=mp140558&role=sit&rNo=0 |title=David John Murray Wright; Anthony Cronin; John Clive ('J.C.') Hall; John Smith; Dannie Abse - National Portrait Gallery |website=www.npg.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n===Poetry Collections===\n* ''The Summer Dance and Other Poems'' (John Lehmann, London 1951)\n* ''The Burning Hare'' (Chatto & Windus / Hogarth Press 1966 )\n* ''A House of Voices'' (Phoenix Living Poet Series, Chatto & Windus/Hogarth, 1973)\n* ''Selected and New Poems 1939-84'' (Secker & Warburg , 1986)\n* ''Long Shadows'' (Shoestring 2003, repr. Faber & Faber 2010)\n\n===Anthologies and Shared Collections===\n* ''Selected Poems'' ([[Keith Douglas]], J.C. Hall, [[Norman Nicholson]]) (1943)\n* ''Mavericks: An Anthology'', ([[Howard Sergeant]] and [[Dannie Abse]] (eds), Editions Poetry and Poverty, London, 1957)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book |last1=Noel-Tod |first1=Jeremy |last2=Hamilton |first2=Ian |year=2013 |title=The Oxford Companion to Modern Poetry in English |location=[[Oxford]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780199640256 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XZKcAQAAQBAJ&dq=J+C+Hall+poet&source=gbs_navlinks_s |ref={{sfnRef|Noel-Tod|Hamilton|2013}}\n }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=asXh39XYCIg Landscape with Figure: World War II poet Keith Douglas  - Hall was recorded for a BBC radio program on Keith Douglas]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, John Clive}}\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Leighton Park School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Oriel College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People from Ealing]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Canadian author|J. C. Hall (disambiguation){{!}}J. C. Hall}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name = J. C. Hall\n| image =\n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = John Clive Hall\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|09|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Ealing, London\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2011|10|14|1920|9|12|df=y}}\n| death_place = Tunbridge Wells, Kent\n| resting_place = \n| occupation = Poet\n| language = English\n| nationality = British\n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Oriel College, Oxford]]\n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp = \n| ethnicity = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n}}\n\n'''John Clive Hall''' (12 September 1920 \u2013 14 October 2011) was an [[England|English]] [[poet]] and editor.\n\n== Poetry ==\nHall's poetry was first published when he was aged seventeen in the anthology, ''The Best Poems of 1938''.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The best Poems of 1938 |last=Moult |first=Thomas |publisher=Jonathan Cape |year=1938 |isbn= |location= |pages=}}</ref> He subsequently wrote and published a trickle of short poems over seven further decades. Not a modernist, he was included in [[Dannie Abse]]'s 'reactionary anthology' ''Mavericks''.<ref>{{Cite book |title= Mavericks - An Anthology |last= |first= |publisher= Editions Poetry And Poverty |year=1957 |isbn= |editor1= Abse, Dannie |editor2= Sergeant, Howard |location= |pages=}}</ref> His work was admired by [[Philip Larkin]] who described it as, \"just the sort of thing I should like to have done myself\" and by [[W. H. Auden]] who wrote \"in the poems of J. C. Hall we see a craftsmanship that yields to the reader constant pleasure and enjoyment. J. C. Hall should be better known.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Long-Shadows-J-C-Hall/dp/0571272657 |title=Long Shadows |first=J. C. |last=Hall |date=19 August 2010 |publisher=Faber & Faber |via=Amazon}}</ref> A Trevor Tolley judged \"his work has a carefulness that makes one ready to accept his small output as a mark of spiritual and poetic integrity\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tolley |first1=A. Trevor |title=The Poetry of the Forties |date=1985 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1708-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/poetryoffortiesi0000toll |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/poetryoffortiesi0000toll/page/258 258] |quote=Fords and Bridges. |language=en}}</ref>.\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in Ealing, London and brought up in [[Royal Tunbridge Wells|Tunbridge Wells]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/8882163/JC-Hall.html |title=J. C. Hall Obituary |date=10 November 2011 |publisher=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=31 December 2017 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Hall attended [[Leighton Park School]] and [[Oriel College, Oxford]].{{sfn|Noel-Tod|Hamilton|2013|p=239}} He was an editor of the literary periodical ''[[Fords and Bridges]]'' at Oxford and became good friends with [[Keith Douglas]].{{sfn|Noel-Tod|Hamilton|2013|p=239}} As a pacifist he did farm work during the war and when Douglas was killed in Normandy, Hall was named as his literary executor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.faber.co.uk/author/jc-hall/ |title=J.C. Hall - Authors - Faber & Faber |website=www.faber.co.uk}}</ref> He worked at ''[[The London Magazine]]'' and at [[Stephen Spender]]'s ''[[Encounter (magazine)|Encounter]]'' as an editor.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He edited the Collected Poems of [[Edwin Muir]] for Faber and Faber in 1952.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Muir |first1=Edwin |title=Collected Poems 1921-1951 |date=1952 |publisher=Faber and Faber}}</ref> A group photographic portrait of Hall, with fellow poets Dannie Abse, [[David Wright (poet)|David John Murray Wright]], [[Anthony Cronin]] and John Smith is held by the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw233563/David-John-Murray-Wright-Anthony-Cronin-John-Clive-JC-Hall-John-Smith-Dannie-Abse?LinkID=mp140558&role=sit&rNo=0 |title=David John Murray Wright; Anthony Cronin; John Clive ('J.C.') Hall; John Smith; Dannie Abse - National Portrait Gallery |website=www.npg.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n===Poetry Collections===\n* ''The Summer Dance and Other Poems'' (John Lehmann, London 1951)\n* ''The Burning Hare'' (Chatto & Windus / Hogarth Press 1966 )\n* ''A House of Voices'' (Phoenix Living Poet Series, Chatto & Windus/Hogarth, 1973)\n* ''Selected and New Poems 1939-84'' (Secker & Warburg , 1986)\n* ''Long Shadows'' (Shoestring 2003, repr. Faber & Faber 2010)\n\n===Anthologies and Shared Collections===\n* ''Selected Poems'' ([[Keith Douglas]], J.C. Hall, [[Norman Nicholson]]) (1943)\n* ''Mavericks: An Anthology'', ([[Howard Sergeant]] and Dannie Abse (eds), Editions Poetry and Poverty, London, 1957)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book |last1=Noel-Tod |first1=Jeremy |last2=Hamilton |first2=Ian |year=2013 |title=The Oxford Companion to Modern Poetry in English |location=[[Oxford]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780199640256 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XZKcAQAAQBAJ&dq=J+C+Hall+poet&source=gbs_navlinks_s |ref={{sfnRef|Noel-Tod|Hamilton|2013}}\n }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=asXh39XYCIg Landscape with Figure: World War II poet Keith Douglas  - Hall was recorded for a BBC radio program on Keith Douglas]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, John Clive}}\n[[Cat